caption: b'Holidays have you overwhelmed? Our gift guide\xe2\x80\x99s\xe2\x80\x8b got you. Head to stories to find unique handpicked presents for home, outdoors, self-care and more in our latest Pop-In shop. #nordstrompop'

b"From our family to yours, we wish you a happy Thanksgiving\xe2\x80\x94we're so thankful for wonderful customers like you. b"The results are in and we\xe2\x80\x99re proud to share that with your help, we raised more than $855,000 for @shoesthatfitcharity\xe2\x80\x94the most we\xe2\x80\x99ve ever raised during our 10-year partnership! b'WE\xe2\x80\x99RE GOING FUR-FREE. By the end of 2021, you\xe2\x80\x99ll no longer find products made using animal fur or exotic animal skin at Nordstrom. 
 
\xe2\x80\x9cAs a leading fashion retailer, we\xe2\x80\x99re committed to delivering the best possible service and merchandise for our customers. Delivering on that commitment means continually listening to customer feedback and evolving our product offering to ensure we\xe2\x80\x99re meeting their needs. As part of our ongoing product evolution, we\xe2\x80\x99ve been working with the @humanesociety of the United States and recently made the decision to stop offering products made with genuine fur or exotic animal skin in any of our stores or online. Our private label brands haven\xe2\x80\x99t used these materials for years, so extending this policy to all the brands we carry is a natural next step for our business.\xe2\x80\x9d
- Teri Bariquit, Nordstrom Chief Merchandising Officer 

Want to learn more about our decision to go fur-free? Head to the link in our bio.'

b"Over the past few months, we\xe2\x80\x99ve done a lot of listening, and we\xe2\x80\x99ve heard from employees, customers, our Board of Directors and Nordstrom partners. 

These conversations have been humbling and educational, and we\xe2\x80\x99ve taken many insights away to help inform our path forward. As we think about our values and who we want to be as a company, it\xe2\x80\x99s clear we have an opportunity to extend ourselves in new ways and set the standard for what Nordstrom represents to our people.

Today, we're sharing with you the biggest pieces of feedback we\xe2\x80\x99ve heard and the specific goals we\xe2\x80\x99ve set to address each. We know there are a lot of ways we can improve as we strive to be a better, more inclusive and anti-racist company for our employees, customers, partners and communities. These concrete actions represent the next phase in our journey, not the finish line. We are committed to doing the work, being transparent about our progress along the way and holding ourselves accountable, and we ask that you continue to help us by giving feedback, sharing ideas and challenging us to grow and evolve. We firmly believe we must focus on the opportunities we have to make Nordstrom a better place for everyone. To read more about our strategy and goals, please visit the link in bio."

b'From our friends at HRC: At the @HumanRightsCampaign, we honor #PrideMonth every year with the deep understanding that Pride started with a protest. b"As people around the world continue to mourn George Floyd today\xe2\x80\x94the day of his funeral\xe2\x80\x94we want to take a moment to honor him, as well as other Black lives senselessly lost. b"We\xe2\x80\x99re on a journey to be better. Our company values stem from the notion that every customer and employee is welcome, respected, appreciated and able to be their authentic self, but we know we still have a lot of work to do. We are committed to being an agent for positive change by listening, continuing important conversations and sharing how we're working to drive meaningful progress at Nordstrom and in our communities. While we have a number of existing programs and efforts underway through our Diversity, Inclusion and Belonging team, we\xe2\x80\x99re not stopping there. b'Black Lives Matter. #BlackoutTuesday'

b'We need change. As a company, we know we have the opportunity to make things better, which is why over the past several years we\'ve amplified our efforts when it comes to diversity, inclusion and belonging at Nordstrom. It begins not only by speaking out, but by listening. Listening to our employees, customers and neighbors as they share what it\'s like to be a person of color in our country today. It\'s working to ensure our teams and leaders represent the diversity we seek. It\'s providing each and every customer who walks in our door the service and experience they expect and deserve to receive at Nordstrom. Our "Courageous Conversation" forums set up by our Black Employee Network have made a big impact on us. These conversations aren\'t easy, but they\'ve never been more important. We\'re grateful for the courage of our employees as they share their stories. We are proud to stand with them. #BlackLivesMatter #NspireChange'

b'This is a painful time for our country and for us. The events going on around all of us are heartbreaking and we want to share a few thoughts with you in this open letter to our employees. 
Pete & Erik Nordstrom

b'Next up in our graduation series is @univpugetsound alumna Bella, who\'s had to pivot her post-college plans in the wake of COVID-19. "I was planning on accepting an internship with a company I really love but the entire internship program was canceled. Since then, I have restarted and adjusted my job search and plan on accepting a non-profit fellowship. This new direction coincides with my desire to use my platform and knowledge to support communities in need and has reaffirmed how important it is to take time to support those most vulnerable. Even if the fellowship is canceled due to COVID-19, I hope to work with a non-profit and give back to the community. Although all logistics of school, work, and life have changed, I am incredibly thankful that I am still graduating and, of course, that I am still healthy. Graduating amid a pandemic is far less than stellar, but it has also refocused my priorities and has reminded me to keep positive because, at this point, that\'s all many of us can really do." b'Back in February we photographed five Seattle-based college students for a feature to celebrate their graduation this summer. Well, things have since shifted dramatically for these young women, so we caught up with them in lockdown to see how they are feeling about the future. We are pleased to report that, from virtual celebrations to never taking anything for granted again, the future remains bright for the class of 2020. \nFirst, hear from @uofwa graduate, Jamie: \xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m sure many can relate when I say that the recent changes in our world have had a tumultuous effect on my daily life. While life pre-quarantine was obviously much better and although I feel a bit like I missed out on the whole \xe2\x80\x9cSenior Spring\xe2\x80\x9d narrative, I\xe2\x80\x99ve learned to find the good in the situation. I live with 16 other girls, and it\xe2\x80\x99s been lovely to be around my friends while quarantining. They are the people who inspire me and keep me going through this. I\xe2\x80\x99ve joked that quarantine is really just our \xe2\x80\x9cultimate bonding experience\xe2\x80\x9d. My lovely roommates and I hope that by the end of June we can put on a faux graduation ceremony on the front lawn of our house and invite our parents to watch (6 feet apart) from the street. Overall, I could not be more grateful for my incredible friends, my supportive family and one thing I know for sure is that I\xe2\x80\x99ll never take my freedom, my health, and my recreational activities for granted again! Cheers to the class of 2020! Be well and stay safe!\xe2\x80\x9d Stay tuned for more graduate features in the coming weeks. #stayNspired'

b'It is with sadness that we have made the tough decision to close all three Jeffrey stores and online business. We want to thank Jeffrey Kalinsky for his contribution to Nordstrom over the last 15 years, to acknowledge the huge impact he\xe2\x80\x99s had on our business and the influence he\xe2\x80\x99s had on the fashion industry since opening his first store in Atlanta, 30 years ago. Jeffrey became the first retailer to open a luxury fashion store in New York\xe2\x80\x99s Meatpacking district when he opened his second store in 1999 and received industry acclaim as not only the first specialty store to offer brands like Gucci and Jil Sander to customers but for forever changing the landscape of the area. A pioneer and champion of talent, his contribution as part of the CFDA Vogue Fashion Fund to support emerging designers and his charitable organization, Jeffrey Cares, are just a few more of the reasons we are proud to have called him a colleague and friend.\nThank you, Jeffrey. We\xe2\x80\x99ll be forever grateful.'

b'As #Nordstrom\'s Senior Vice President of Human Resources, Farrell Redwine specializes in people. How they work, where they work best and the things that will best set them up for success. Farrell recently shared with us her own experience navigating the corporate world as a Black woman, along with how she hopes her success will inspire others: "If I had a couple of words that encapsulate my career journey as a Black female and now at an executive level, it would be \'the only one.\' It\'s not often that I am at a table with others who look like me. It\'s hard to articulate how that feels, but what it has manifested for me is resiliency and a strong desire to bring others along by serving as a role model for other Black women, being a mentor to many and making career choices where I can remain true to who I am as an individual\xe2\x80\x94my style, personality and values. One of the things I value about Nordstrom is that we are an organization that fosters a culture of belonging, and we are increasingly focused on diverse representation throughout the company." Want to learn more about Farrell and other incredible Nordstrom leaders? Head to the link in bio for interviews with three female African American execs about climbing the corporate ladder\xe2\x80\x94and what businesses need to do to create a more inclusive environment. Remember. Educate. Celebrate.'

"Tracee Ellis Ross. She\'s positive and always cheering on others with a huge smile. She embodies the essence of what it means to be carefree and beautifully black." And on the topic of Flo\'s career, she had this to say: "The most important thing I\'ve learned in my career so far is not every action deserves a reaction. b'We continue to celebrate Black History Month with Shante, one of the department managers at our Downtown Seattle store. Shante shared her biggest career challenge with us and why she looks to Michelle Obama as a source of empowerment and inspiration. "Navigating career growth while staying true to my own goals and ambitions can be really challenging. When it feels like peers are moving faster than I am and getting exciting opportunities, it can be easy to question my own path and pace. It\'s important to stay true to my core values and say, \'No, thank you\' when I know a potential opportunity is out of alignment with what\'s important to me and where I want to go." "Michelle Obama is such an inspiration to me! She has demonstrated, on a global platform, what it looks like to reject the limitations others try to impose on black women. It\'s not often you see black women in high-level positions, and too often, we see each other get overlooked, disregarded or excluded altogether. Not only has she not let those factors deter her from pursuing success, but she also uses her platform to pull more of us up behind her." Get to know more of the amazing African American team members that help make #Nordstrom great at the link in bio, and stay tuned as we feature more employees throughout the month! Remember. Educate. Celebrate.'

b'We\'ve loved introducing our amazing team members to you as we celebrate Black History Month, spotlighting their incredible advice, stories and more. Next, meet Brandon, a member of our marketing team. Brandon told us the advice he\'d give his younger self, and we couldn\'t agree more: "I would tell a younger version of myself not to seek validation from other people. There were a lot of early times in my career where I stumbled trying to say or do what I thought my leaders wanted vs. coming to the table with a clearly defined idea of my own. Over the years, I\'ve found the most important thing I can do for myself is have a clearly defined point of view that I can confidently articulate and support that solves the need at hand. While people may not always approve or agree, they will at least know where I stand." Meet more of the #Nordstrom team as we highlight employees and their stories throughout the month! Remember. Educate. Celebrate.'

b'Meet Beverly Mills, #Nordstrom\'s Vice President, Divisional Merchandise Manager, Kids\' Wear. From buyer to VP, Beverly let us in on what she\'s learned in her career and how other Black women climbing the corporate ladder can succeed. In short? Be a woman with a plan: "Be an active participant in driving your future. Have an objective in mind and a solid, realistic reason why that particular goal was chosen. Formulate a plan, work the plan and own the outcome. Be an advocate for yourself and don\'t be afraid to self-promote, in a humble way. You\'ll soon realize that the more you share, the more others will see the value in working alongside you and want to be on your team. Keep your eyes open and stay humble with every success." Continue celebrating Black History Month with us at the link in bio where you can learn more about Beverly and other inspiring Nordstrom leaders, and stay tuned as we highlight more employees and their stories throughout the month! b'Continuing our celebration of Black History Month with Christopher Guest, a Senior Project Manager with our Diversity, Inclusion & Belonging team. Read on as Christopher talks through his experience navigating corporate America and the African American leader that\xe2\x80\x99s inspired him along the way: 
On corporate America:
\xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m incredibly grateful to have a position where my voice and opinions are respected, valued, and heard. I am on a high-performing team where my manager and her manager are both women of color, and through their leadership they make space for me and I know that I belong. That has not always been the case.\xe2\x80\x9d On the person he\xe2\x80\x99s looked to for inspiration:
\xe2\x80\x9cBayard Rustin was a civil rights leader that advocated for more than just black advancement. He was a humanitarian and a gay rights activist as well and he did most of his work behind the scenes. I respect and honor the fact that he worked behind the scenes with several leaders such as Dr. King, and A. Philip Randolph to impact the world.\xe2\x80\x9d Meet more of the #Nordstrom team as we highlight employees and their stories throughout the month! Remember. Educate. Celebrate.'

b'Celebrating Black History Month: all month long we\xe2\x80\x99ll be spotlighting eight African American employees at Nordstrom, talking through their experiences as well as what companies can\xe2\x80\x94and need\xe2\x80\x94to do differently to ensure their workforces are inclusive. First up: meet Maegan, a member of our merchandising team. 
When it comes to the advice Maegan would give her younger self, her response is one to remember:
\xe2\x80\x9cThere will be a lot of moments where you will question yourself and doubt your place in the world. You may think people don\xe2\x80\x99t see you and wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t care if you weren\xe2\x80\x99t here. Not only is that untrue but you are masking gifts you have been given by listening to those negative voices. It will get better and you will find your voice and your wings to fly. Turn on your light and shine it bright and you will be unstoppable. You are loved, important and meant to be here. Don\xe2\x80\x99t stop now you have more to give to the world.\xe2\x80\x9d Meet more of the #Nordstrom team as we highlight employees and their stories throughout the month! 
Remember. Educate. Celebrate.'
